		<item>
		<title>Google Ads Not Working? Try These 7 Fixes</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-not-working</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Michelle Morgan]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 16 Jun 2025 12:30:42 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Google Ads]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=92095</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Follow these steps to take your under-performing Google Ads from zero to hero.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-not-working">Google Ads Not Working? Try These 7 Fixes</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It happens all the time. You do your best to build out a set of campaigns in Google Ads that follow industry best practices and that are aimed at your goals, but you just aren‚Äôt seeing the results you‚Äôre looking for. So what do you do?</p>
<p>Luckily, there are some pretty common issues that arise to cause poor performance and, for the most part, they can be pretty easily addressed assuming you‚Äôre willing to put in a little elbow grease.</p>
<p>Here‚Äôs a list of the things you should be looking at to get your performance turned around and make sure you‚Äôre hitting the goals you‚Äôre out to achieve.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ol>
<li><a href="#check-your-conversion-tracking-setup">Check your conversion tracking setup</a></li>
<li><a href="#look-into-your-goal-optimization-settings">Look into your goal optimization settings</a></li>
<li><a href="#adjust-your-bid-strategies">Adjust your bid strategies</a></li>
<li><a href="#evaluate-your-targeting">Evaluate your targeting</a></li>
<li><a href="#determine-whether-or-not-you-have-segment-inefficiencies">Determine whether or not you have segment inefficiencies</a></li>
<li><a href="#assess-your-copy-and-landing-pages">Assess your copy and landing pages</a></li>
<li><a href="#get-on-a-good-optimization-schedule">Get on a good optimization schedule</a></li>
</ol>
<h2>How to fix poor-performing Google Ads in 7 steps</h2>
<p>Follow these steps to turn your performance around.</p>
<div id="check-your-conversion-tracking-setup"></div>
<h3>1. Check your conversion tracking setup</h3>
<p>A foundational aspect of paid media campaigns is their trackability. It‚Äôs one of the key factors that sets these campaigns apart from other tactics. But it can also be a very easy mistake to overlook when trying to figure out why performance isn‚Äôt where you want it.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-active-conversion-settings.webp" alt="conversion settings in google ads showing status" width="900" height="350" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92102" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-active-conversion-settings.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-active-conversion-settings-480x187.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Whenever I have a campaign that has started performing poorly, or that has never performed well, I always go back and check on the conversion tracking setup to ensure everything is working well. Only when that‚Äôs confirmed do I move on to other potential issues.</p>
<h4><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2705.png" alt="‚úÖ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Action items</h4>
<ul>
<li>Confirm your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/08/14/how-to-use-google-tag-manager">Google Tag</a> is on all pages of your website.</li>
<li>Confirm your conversion pixels are firing on the right pages or events for all individual conversion actions on your site.</li>
</ul>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f6a8.png" alt="üö®" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want a quick look at where you can make improvements to your Google Ads campaigns? </strong>Get an¬†instant audit &gt;&gt; <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader">Free Google Ads Performance Grader</a></p>
<div id="look-into-your-goal-optimization-settings"></div>
<h3>2. Look into your goal optimization settings</h3>
<p>Just because your conversion actions are firing properly doesn‚Äôt mean we‚Äôre finished with <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/04/17/how-to-set-up-google-ads-enhanced-conversions">conversion action setup</a>. Depending on how you have your account set up, you can be either prioritizing or de-prioritizing different conversion events.</p>
<p>Here are three things to look into:</p>
<h4>Account default goals</h4>
<p>In the conversion manager, each action item is organized into a conversion category. That conversion category is then considered either an account default goal, meaning the conversion actions in that category will be counted in the conversions column, or not.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-account-default-goals.webp" alt="google ads account default goals" width="900" height="350" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92103" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-account-default-goals.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-account-default-goals-480x187.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>If the conversion actions you‚Äôre trying to optimize for are not in an account default goal category, then you may need to make some adjustments. (There are other settings you can use to overcome this that we‚Äôll cover soon.)</p>
<h4>Secondary vs. Primary goals</h4>
<p>Issues can arise when your conversion action is set to a Secondary goal rather than a Primary one. Primary goals are counted in the conversions column and used as optimization events for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-smart-bidding">Smart Bidding</a>, but Secondary actions are not used as optimization signals and are only counted in the All Conversions column&#8211;not Conversions.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-secondary-goal.webp" alt="google ads secondary goal" width="786" height="498" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92105" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-secondary-goal.webp 786w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-secondary-goal-480x304.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 786px, 100vw" /></p>
<h4>Individual campaign setting goals</h4>
<p>At the campaign level, advertisers can opt to use account-level or campaign-level conversions. If your campaigns are set up to focus on conversions that are different from your account-level goals, that could also be causing issues in performance.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-campaign-specific-conversion-goals.webp" alt="google ads campaign specific goal" width="900" height="317" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92106" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-campaign-specific-conversion-goals.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-campaign-specific-conversion-goals-480x169.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<h4><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2705.png" alt="‚úÖ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Action items</h4>
<ul>
<li>Confirm all conversion tracking is working properly.</li>
<li>Ensure all account default goals are set up to your liking.</li>
<li>Make sure all goals are assigned either Primary or Secondary status as needed.</li>
<li>Don‚Äôt forget to confirm that all campaign-level settings are in line with your goals.</li>
</ul>
<div id="adjust-your-bid-strategies"></div>
<h3>3. Adjust your bid strategies</h3>
<p>All of the Google Ads bid strategies are designed to do a very specific thing, so if you‚Äôre using the wrong one, it could be causing issues.</p>
<p>For the most part, all of these bid strategies are pretty self-explanatory. Maximize Conversions and Maximize Conversion Value work to get you good results, but sometimes they can be less efficient than those same bid strategies with additional controls like <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/31/google-retiring-tcpa-troas">tCPA and tROAS</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/google-ads-bidding-strategies-smart.jpg" alt="google ads bidding strategies" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91784" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/google-ads-bidding-strategies-smart.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/google-ads-bidding-strategies-smart-480x308.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>But in addition to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/12/19/google-ads-automated-bidding">picking the right bid strategy</a>, it‚Äôs also important to make sure the bid strategy is set up for success. Smart Bidding requires enough success points and wiggle room to see results.</p>
<p>Here are some common problems we see with bid strategies that hinder performance:</p>
<h4>Unrealistic goals</h4>
<p>While we would all like to have extremely high ROAS or <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead">super low CPLs</a>, that doesn‚Äôt mean they‚Äôre realistic and achievable in the long run. To help keep your goals realistic, start out with targets that are in line with your performance as a business.</p>
<p>If your entire site sees a 300% ROI, then 300% is likely a reasonable ROAS to set. When you leverage unrealistic goals, like 1,000% ROAS on a site with 300% ROI, you‚Äôll stifle the bid strategy, and it will slowly stop serving ads since it likely can‚Äôt hit your target.</p>
<h4>Limited performance indicators</h4>
<p>A common issue I see with bid strategies centers around the volume of conversions being tracked. A general rule of thumb is one conversion per day.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-smart-bidding-suggestion-for-volume.webp" alt="google ads smart bidding volume suggestion" width="900" height="185" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92108" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-smart-bidding-suggestion-for-volume.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-smart-bidding-suggestion-for-volume-480x99.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>If your account (not campaign, account) isn‚Äôt averaging at least 30 conversions in 30 days, then you might not have enough volume to optimize for that action.</p>
<p>Without those positive indicators coming in regularly, Google won‚Äôt get enough positive signals that a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/conversion-rate-optimization-marketing">click leads to a conversion</a> and will, again, slowly stop serving ads.</p>
<h4>Restricted budgets</h4>
<p>Even if you have realistic goals and enough conversion volume, keeping your budget too low can cause issues. Yes, we know Google always tells you to increase your budget, but this could be a performance killer.</p>
<p>If your target CPL is $100, but your daily budget is only $50, then you‚Äôre setting that campaign up to hit only one conversion every couple of days, falling below our regular rule of thumb.</p>
<h4>Not adjusting bid strategies with time</h4>
<p>Just because a bid strategy works for you for a time, that doesn‚Äôt mean it will work forever. You may need to change bid strategies or tweak the settings for that bid strategy over time. These require regular maintenance and adjustment right alongside all the other aspects within your account.</p>
<h4><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2705.png" alt="‚úÖ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Action items</h4>
<ul>
<li>Review your bid strategies and ensure they‚Äôre the right ones to achieve your goals.</li>
<li>Be sure the goals for your campaigns are realistic.</li>
<li>Ensure your campaigns have enough budget for your bid strategy to operate.</li>
<li>Only use Smart Bidding strategies for conversion actions that have enough volume to support the machine learning cycles.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-audit">Regularly review your bid strategy settings and performance</a>, and don‚Äôt be afraid to test and iterate as needed to keep seeing strong results.</li>
</ul>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4b0.png" alt="üí∞" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>How much should you be spending on Google Ads?</strong> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/google-ads-industry-benchmarks?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Guide_2025GoogleAdsBenchmarks_Download&amp;itm_source=wordstream&amp;itm_medium=blog&amp;itm_campaign=incontent_links">Get our latest Google Ads Benchmarks to find out</a>.</p>
<div id="evaluate-your-targeting"></div>
<h3>4. Evaluate your targeting</h3>
<p>There are tons of different types of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-audience-targeting">targeting options in Google Ads</a>, and depending on what your goals are, many of them can cause issues with your performance.</p>
<p>Let&#8217;s look into a few targeting options to evaluate:</p>
<h4>Keyword match types</h4>
<p>Even though Google loves them, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/03/29/succeed-with-google-ads-broad-match">Broad match terms</a> can reach a very wide range of users. They have the widest reach of all the match types and can end up showing for quite a bit of traffic that isn‚Äôt relevant to your business. Broad match isn‚Äôt categorically bad, but without oversight, it can get out of hand very quickly.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/keyword-match-types-broad-match-png.webp" alt="keyword match types chart with arrow pointing to broad match" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-90367" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/keyword-match-types-broad-match-png.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/03/keyword-match-types-broad-match-480x308.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<h4>Performance Max</h4>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/05/01/is-performance-max-right-for-you">Performance Max</a> targets users across all networks within the Google Ads ecosystem, and each of those placements has their own set of best practices when it comes to targeting.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/performance-max-placements.webp" alt="performance max placements" width="900" height="424" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92109" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/performance-max-placements.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/performance-max-placements-480x226.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Within the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/01/23/optimize-performance-max-campaigns">Performance Max campaign setup</a>, you have some controls over where you show, but they‚Äôre less specific than other campaign types. <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/12/11/search-themes-for-performance-max-campaigns">Search themes</a> are just suggestions, not keywords. Audience signals are just a starting point for targeting, not exclusive targeting settings that Google stays within.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/performance-max-search-themes.webp" alt="google performance max search themes" width="900" height="728" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92110" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/performance-max-search-themes.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/performance-max-search-themes-480x388.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Without full control over those targeting settings, you could see good results from Google‚Äôs machine learning, or you could struggle to hit goals as their system gets further from your intended targets.</p>
<h4>Optimized targeting</h4>
<p>In Display campaigns, there‚Äôs a setting that operates similarly to the expansion tactics in Performance Max&#8211;<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/22/google-ads-optimized-targeting">Optimized Targeting</a>. The difference is that you can opt out of this within Display campaigns.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-display-optimized-targeting.png" alt="google display optimized targeting" width="900" height="295" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92111" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-display-optimized-targeting.png 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-display-optimized-targeting-480x157.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Google will warn you that your campaigns might not perform as well, but if the expansion is the reason for the low performance, then you‚Äôre likely on the right path.</p>
<h4><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2705.png" alt="‚úÖ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Action items</h4>
<ul>
<li>Review your targeting to ensure you‚Äôre reaching the right people.</li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/search-term">Review search queries</a> to determine if your match types need to be tightened up.</li>
<li>Opt out of Optimized Targeting for Display campaigns.</li>
<li>Test using other campaign types other than Performance Max.</li>
</ul>
<div id="determine-whether-or-not-you-have-segment-inefficiencies"></div>
<h3>5. Determine whether or not you have segment inefficiencies</h3>
<p>Expanding on the idea of targeting inefficiencies, some pockets of performance aren‚Äôt necessarily targeting but are still sneaky subsets of targeting that can drive your account to underperform.</p>
<h4>Network problems</h4>
<p>For Search campaigns, you can opt into the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-search-partner-insights">Search Partner Network</a>, which is an expanded network of listings on sites other than Google, but powered by Google Search. These placements can range from totally legit to completely sketchy.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-network-segmentation-report.webp" alt="google ads network segmentation report" width="900" height="298" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92112" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-network-segmentation-report.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-network-segmentation-report-480x159.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Whenever I have bad performance in a Search campaign, one of the first places I look is at the Search Partner performance. On the campaigns tab, just segment your data by Network, and you‚Äôll see how it‚Äôs doing compared to regular Google Search.</p>
<p>If things look bad, you can opt out in your campaign settings.</p>
<p>While we‚Äôre here, this brings up another Network issue. By default, Google will opt Search campaigns into the Display Network. Please, please, please, don‚Äôt do this. If you want a cross-platform campaign, use Performance Max. Just uncheck this box every time.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-display-network-opt-out.webp" alt="opt out of google display network" width="900" height="234" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92113" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-display-network-opt-out.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-display-network-opt-out-480x125.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<h4>Device performance</h4>
<p>Another segment you can check on is Device. If you‚Äôre alive in 2025, you‚Äôre probably more than aware of the differences between being on a mobile device vs. a computer vs. a tablet vs. a television. Those differences can cause performance variance between the device categories.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, Google has kind of buried the Device report in the newly rearranged interface. You can find your accounts‚Äô device performance in the Insights and Reports section, in the When and Where Ads Showed report, then choose the Devices tab. Depending on the other settings for your campaign, you can either opt out of a device category as a whole or you can adjust your bids to be more or less aggressive for a specific device category.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-device-performance.webp" alt="google ads device performance" width="900" height="390" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92114" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-device-performance.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-device-performance-480x208.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<h4>Additional segments to review</h4>
<p>Other categories that are good to check include your Ad Scheduling, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/10/17/google-ads-location-targeting">Location targeting</a>, and Audience segments. These can each be found in different sections of the interface and don‚Äôt typically have runaway poor performance, but each could be the key to finding smaller-scale inefficiencies that cause performance to be lower than desired.</p>
<h4><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2705.png" alt="‚úÖ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Action items</h4>
<ul>
<li>Keep Search campaigns focused on Search and opt out of the Display network.</li>
<li>Understand how different device categories, locations, ad schedules, and audience segments are performing in your account and adjust as needed.</li>
</ul>
<div id="assess-your-copy-and-landing-pages"></div>
<h3>6. Assess your copy and landing pages</h3>
<p>Google Ads campaigns definitely have lots of technical considerations that go into them to see good performance. The previous sections should highlight that pretty well.</p>
<p>But these campaigns also require you to have a personal marketing touch, which means the content and designs that feed your campaigns need to be compelling and user-friendly.</p>
<p>One problem area can be your ad copy. If your ads aren‚Äôt coherent and or action-oriented, you likely won‚Äôt see good results. There are tons of resources available that can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-copy">help you write great ads</a>. Just take advantage.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/google-ads-benchmarks-example-ads-on-serp.webp" alt="google ads benchmarks - example ad serp" width="800" height="379" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-91526" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/google-ads-benchmarks-example-ads-on-serp.webp 800w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/google-ads-benchmarks-example-ads-on-serp-480x227.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 800px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Get <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/24/google-ads-examples">Google Ads examples</a> here for inspiration.</em></p>
<p>The same goes for your landing page. If the landing page is particularly slow, light on details, or is laid out confusingly, you‚Äôre likely not going to see the conversions you want from your campaigns. Again, there are <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/adwords-landing-page">so</a> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/01/15/landing-page-best-practices">many</a> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/06/10/high-converting-landing-pages">resources</a> available for you to review to get ideas.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/landing-page-elements.webp" alt="landing page elements" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92115" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/landing-page-elements.webp 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/landing-page-elements-480x308.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<h4><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2705.png" alt="‚úÖ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Action items</h4>
<ul>
<li>Retain the human angle when <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/05/responsive-search-ad-copy">writing new copy</a> or developing new landing pages.</li>
<li>Make sure your ad copy is coherent, relevant, compelling, and creates interest.</li>
<li>Create landing pages that follow industry best practices, have <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/09/call-to-action">clear calls to action</a>, use relevant supporting information, and limit friction to conversion.</li>
</ul>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f680.png" alt="üöÄ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Want to know what makes a stand-out landing page?</strong> Download the guide &gt;&gt; <a href="https://marketing.localiq.com/WSLiQContentDLHowToMakeGreatLandingPages.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_LandingPages_HowToMakeGreatLandingPagesGuide_Download">How to Make Great Landing Pages (with Crazy High Conversions)</a></p>
<div id="get-on-a-good-optimization-schedule"></div>
<h3>7. Get on a good optimization schedule</h3>
<p>Just because you put in all that time and effort to launch a shiny new campaign strategy doesn‚Äôt mean it‚Äôs going to perform well forever. These are living, breathing things and need to be regularly maintained to see good results.</p>
<h4>Regular optimizations</h4>
<p>If you‚Äôre not regularly optimizing your account, you‚Äôre likely going to see issues. The good news is that the regular cadence of optimizations addresses many of the points in this post, but also, WordStream has a ton of posts that you can review to see all sorts of things you should be doing to your accounts at all times.</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/adwords-optimization">A Simple Guide to Google Ads Optimization</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/08/24/google-ads-optimization">4 Killer Google Ads Optimizations to Stretch Your Budget Further</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/11/04/optimize-google-local-advertising">10 Expert Tips to Optimize Your Google Local Advertising</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-audit-pmax-display-video">5 Ways to Optimize Google PMAX, Video, &amp; Display Campaigns</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-to-run-google-ads">How to Run Google Ads: The Step-by-Step Recipe for Success</a></li>
</ul>
<h4>Automated optimizations</h4>
<p>Although you might think it‚Äôs in your best interest, one of the other problems I regularly see with accounts is when optimizations are left to the machines. Despite what they may say, Google doesn‚Äôt always know what your goals are with their automated optimizations. Some of them can be good, but without regular human oversight, they can ‚Äúoptimize‚Äù your account right into the ground.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-automated-optimizations.webp" alt="google ads automated optimizations option" width="900" height="245" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92116" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-automated-optimizations.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/google-ads-automated-optimizations-480x131.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The Auto Apply Recommendations within Google Ads are easily turned off by visiting the Recommendations tab, then clicking the Auto-apply icon in the upper right of the screen, then turning off any or all of the automatic updates.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/turn-off-automated-optimizations.webp" alt="how to turn off automated optimizations in google ads" width="900" height="528" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-92117" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/turn-off-automated-optimizations.webp 900w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/turn-off-automated-optimizations-480x282.webp 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 900px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>There are also Automated <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-assets">Assets</a> that Google opts every account into that you can remove. <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rJKIe7c-9W8" target="_blank" rel="noopener">These have a few more hidden steps to deactivate</a>, but can be well worth it.</p>
<h4><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2705.png" alt="‚úÖ" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Action items</h4>
<ul>
<li>Create a regular cadence of tasks to execute on your account and stick to it.</li>
<li>Don‚Äôt let Google make changes on your behalf that you‚Äôre not aware of. Opt out of the recommendations you don‚Äôt want and keep the ones you‚Äôre okay with.</li>
<li>Do the same for Automatically Applied Assets and make sure all customer-facing messaging is approved by you.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Fix poor-performing Google Ads fast</h2>
<p>Low performance in a Google Ads account isn‚Äôt a death knell. In almost every scenario, there‚Äôs something you can do about it. Hopefully, this rundown has given you ideas of where to look for poor performance influences and what to do about them when you find them (and check out this guide to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/gmail-ads">Gmail Ads</a> while you&#8217;re at it). But if you need more help, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/marketing-services?cid=Web_WS_InContent_Demo_Blog_Demo">reach out for a demo</a> to see how we can fix your Google Ads for you fast.</p>
